Will they reply, That saith and a good will, and the act of a beneficial application, are not the special gifts of the Holy Spirit? They will be ashamed of such gross Pelagianisni. Let them, then, con- fess with us, That as through the death of Christ special benefits are procured for the elect, so there was in the will of Christ in dying, and of God the Father in accepting his death, an effectual intention of procuring and confer- ring them. And this is that singular privilege in the death of Christ which we claim for the elect alone3 because it appears from the fact, that God has destined that they alone should be effectually saved by the death of his Son. From whence (Heb. vii. 25) he is stated to be the Saviour of some, that is, of the elect, altogether, viz. both meri- toriously and efficaciously.
